column24: general. You will see a video of a driving session in a highly automated vehicle.  The vehicle takes over lateral and longitudinal control (braking, accelerating, steering).  The vehicle attempts to (1) detect objects in the scene and (2) recognize the intent of pedestrians:   1. Object Detection:  Detected vehicles, pedestrians and traffic lights are marked in color. The marking is realized by coloring the respective object.The following color assignment applies: pedestrians and cyclists are marked in red, vehicles are marked in blue, and traffic lights as well as traffic signs are marked in yellow.                 2. Pedestrian Intention Recognition:  While driving, a symbol is displayed above detected pedestrians. Symbols above people whose intention has been safely detected are displayed in two colors:They are displayed in light blue if the intention is to stay on the sidewalk, or in dark blue if the intention is to cross the street.Symbols over people whose intention was not recognized with certainty are displayed in yellow.   While watching the video, you are supposed to imagine sitting in such an automated vehicle, follow the entire journey attentively, and then assess it.   Make sure your speakers are turned on.  Please click "Yes" if you understand.   You will have to start the video. Fullscreen will be enabled automatically. Scriptblockers have to be disabled.  You will not be able to go to the next page until after the video was shown completely.

column86: feedback. Here, you can give open feedback regarding concerns, improvement proposals, and other thoughts.
None

The pedestrian awareness system was inconsistent and inaccurate. It frequently assigned pedestrian status to things that weren't pedestrians. It frequently predicted the actions of pedestrians inaccurately. It frequently labeled pedestrians as having one status (for example, being on the sidewalk) when they were clearly of another status (for example, in the street).

I was able to see all pedestrians, vehicles and signs colorized like they were supposed to be. I did not notice any defects in the car's self driving actions, and cannot think of any way to do it differently.
This exercise was enjoyable. Thank you for allowing med to participate. Have a wonderful day.
It would be helpful to have a timer on the video so I know how much more time I have left for watching the video
Maybe changing colors for upcoming pedestrians or anticipating them. Blue was used for the cars and the anticipating pedestrians.
All was well thank you!
I've no feedback or concerns.

My biggest concerns would be how is it predicting other road dangers like a tree falls suddenly into the road. Would it detect the tree on it's way down and start to stop like we would if driving manually or would the car stop once it's sees that it is an obstruction on the road. I would want a car that could detect things quicker than me and in this experience it didn't seem to recognize all the other things outside of the road like lamp posts, buildings, etc.
I was very impressed with the vehicle's visual cues and decision making overall.
the study worked perfectly with no issues. my only concern is the sensors were reading cars as pedestrians and i don't know why it would do that.
The simulation video is entirely too long.
I think if you could give more views of the front of the vehicle it would be helpful.
The only concern I had was with the constant changing of predictions when there was a lot of pedestrians.
At one point I felt the vehicle was too close to a vehicle in front of it. Also, some of the pedestrians prediction seemed off or delayed.
I thought the vehicle drove safely and smoothly. It was easy to predict what the vehicle was going to do next
It had a lot of difficulty predicting what people would do and in some cases got it wrong.

Very very interesting! I was watching the traffic in a whole new way, the icons above the pedestrians were very cool to see. I like watching the predictions on there movements. I have to say technology is amazing!
The automated vehicle did not always do what I thought.  Such as when turning a corner is went to the far left lane and should have turned into the far right lane.
It missed a handful of people at a bus stop and didn't identify the guy in the moped until almost at the end.
No additional feedback.

Maybe just highlight all the pedestrians so i know the car is registering them and only mark the pedestrians who are crossing the road with a higher threshhold, so I know on which pedestrians the car is reacting.

I think the constant use of trying to figure out if a pedestrian will cross or not was a lot and had many inaccuracies due to changing direction of people.
Nothing at this point
Engaging and interesting project.

I found the signs and lights being in color very distracting as many signs are color coded and I was worried I might not be able to accurately tell the lights changing to the correct color if they were in a different order than I am used to. I prefer to be able to clearly identify if a sign is red, orange, blue, etc. I found the altering of my color perception  very uncomfortable.

The vehicle also seemed to struggle to identify motorcycles, mopeds and bikes as vehicles or people depending on the situation. It would be nice to have some sort of indication of the path the vehicle intends to take as well as a wider viewpoint at times.
